{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11920"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11920"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.2,0.61,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101492"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4517"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83931"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"833"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43281"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101492"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with severe pain in his left leg. The pain began suddenly this morning after he lost his footing while walking up stairs. He describes a sensation as though he had \u0027been kicked in the calf\u0027 and instinctively turned around to look for the cause, but saw nothing. He was unable to walk at the scene and has had to hobble to the clinic. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. He does not take any regular medications other than antihypertensives and a statin. He leads a sedentary lifestyle and spends most of his free time using virtual reality goggles and playing video games. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is swelling of the distal calf, and he is unable to stand on tiptoe on the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be positive?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lachman test","Homan\u0027s sign","Simmonds-Thompson test","McMurray test","Anterior ankle drawer test"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario describes a classic presentation of Achilles tendon rupture: sudden onset pain in the calf after a minor trauma, a sensation of being kicked, and difficulty walking. Those most at risk of this type of injury are middle-aged men, those with a sedentary lifestyle and athletes.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EOther risk factors include fluoroquinolone (\u0027-floxacin\u0027) antibiotics, steroid injections, and chronic inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive \u003Cstrong\u003ESimmonds-Thompson test\u003C/strong\u003E is highly suggestive of this diagnosis. This test is performed by squeezing the calf while the patient lies prone with feet hanging off the bed; absence of plantar flexion indicates a ruptured Achilles tendon. Imaging such as ultrasound or magnetic resonance imaging can confirm the diagnosis, but clinical examination is often sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELachman test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess the integrity of the anterior cruciate ligament in the knee. It is not relevant to injuries of the Achilles tendon or calf.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHoman\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E is a historical test for deep vein thrombosis, elicited by dorsiflexing the foot to see if it causes calf pain. It is neither sensitive nor specific and is not used to diagnose Achilles tendon rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMcMurray test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect meniscal injury in the knee by flexing and rotating the knee while extending it. It is not relevant to calf or Achilles tendon injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior ankle drawer test\u003C/strong\u003E assesses the integrity of the anterior talofibular ligament, commonly injured in ankle sprains. It does not test for Achilles tendon rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A positive Simmonds-Thompson test (absence of plantar flexion when the calf is squeezed) is highly suggestive of Achilles tendon rupture.","Achilles tendon rupture typically presents with sudden onset calf pain, often described as a sensation of being kicked, and difficulty walking.","Other special tests such as Lachman, McMurray, and anterior ankle drawer are used for knee and ankle ligament injuries, not Achilles tendon rupture."],"references":["Douglas J, Kelly M, Blachut P. Clarification of the Simmonds-Thompson test for rupture of an Achilles tendon. Can J Surg. 2009 Jun;52(3):E40-1. PMID: 19503640; PMCID: PMC2689757. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2689757/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83931"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11920"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83931"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T10:54:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T10:55:18+09:30"}